Introduction

In this file we will predict the log of wages using some machine learning algorithms. First, we will explore the data and present data visualization. Second, we will walk through the models we have used. Afterwards, we will compare the different models based on predictive power (interpretability with DALEX). Finally, we will predict using the model we found best for our purposes.

About PSID

Panel Study of Income Dynamics (PSID) is a panel survey of families in the US, conducted by the University of Michigan. The PSID measures economic, social, and health factors over the life course of families over multiple generations. Data have been collected from the same families and their descendants since 1968. As of 2013, the PSID had information on over 75,000 individuals, spanning as many as 4 decades of their lives. The data set we received is a subset taken from the PSID database.

Correlation of log of wage with the main features:

Here we calculated the correlations of all the features on the lnwage in order to better understand which of them are the most correlated with the wage. based on that information we will choose the interactions that will be created. the maximum correlation is around +- 0.4 . Not surprisingly, the most correlated feature is edu2. Only afterwards, we found the female variable as expected. Afterwards, come the following features:: education years, colldeg (college degree), south (geographically), black and manager.

correl <- train_set_corr %>%
  data.frame() %>%
  cor()

correl[lower.tri(correl,diag=TRUE)]=NA # put NA
correl<-as.data.frame(as.table(correl)) # as a dataframe
correl<-na.omit(correl) # remove NA
correl<-correl[with(correl, order(-Freq)), ]
correl<- correl[correl$Var1 == "lnwage",]

correl<- correl[correl$Freq >= 0.2 | correl$Freq <= -0.2 ,]

correl %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Var2 , y= Freq)) +
  geom_col(aes( fill = Freq)) +
   xlab('Variables') +
 ylab('') +
  ggtitle("Correlation with lnwage") +
  labs(fill = "Correlation") +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom",
      plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Several density plots of log of wage divided by the main features:

In these plots, we can see how the distribution of log of wage changes as we divide the data. First, we can see that the distribution of the log of wages of the subset of college graduates is more skewed to the right compared to the complementing subset. We observe similar patterns in the divisions to white and black (white earn more, on average) and males and females (males earn more, on average). This meets our expectations, as we know that education is positively correlated with wage, and there is a wage gap between white and black people, and the gender gap is still substantial. However, we can that when we divide the data by the south dummy variable, the difference in means does not seem very substantial.

log_sex_mean <- ddply(train_set_viz, "female", summarise, grp.mean=mean(lnwage))

Getting ready for the model estimation

Interactions and variables generating

First of all, based on the analysis above, we will create several interactions and a variable for the square value of education years:

train_set<- train_set %>%
  mutate(fem_edu = female*edyrs,
         fem_col = female*colldeg,
         fem_bl = female*black,
         fem_so = female*south,
         bl_so = black*south,
         bl_edu =black*edyrs,
         bl_col = black*colldeg,
         edu2 = edyrs*edyrs,
         so_edu = south*edyrs
         ) 


test_set<- test_set %>%
  mutate(fem_edu = female*edyrs,
         fem_col = female*colldeg,
         fem_bl = female*black,
         fem_so = female*south,
         bl_so = black*south,
         bl_edu =black*edyrs,
         bl_col = black*colldeg,
         edu2 = edyrs*edyrs,
         so_edu = south*edyrs
         )

Splitting the train_set data for training and test sets:

set.seed(1994)
data_split<- initial_split(train_set, prop = 0.7)
train_set1 <- training(data_split)
test_set1 <- testing(data_split)
x_train <- train_set1[, c(3:48)] %>%
  data.matrix()
y_train <- train_set1$lnwage
    
x_test <- test_set1[, c(3:48)] %>%
    data.matrix()
y_test <- test_set1$lnwage  
    
test_set_noID <- data.matrix(test_set[, c(2:47)])

Models

Ridge regularization with Cross validation

The first model we will use will be a model with ridge regularization:

fit_ridge <- glmnet(x_train, y_train, alpha = 0)
fit_ridge %>% 
  plot(xvar = "lambda")

cv_fit <- cv.glmnet(x_train, y_train, alpha = 0)
cv_fit %>%
  plot()

Picking lambda:

pred_cv_min <- as.vector(predict(cv_fit, s = "lambda.min", newx = x_test))
pred_cv_1se <- as.vector(predict(cv_fit, s = "lambda.1se", newx = x_test))
  
  
comp_models <- data.frame("Min Lambda" = pred_cv_min, pred_cv_1se)
 
comp_models %>%
  tidy()

Let’s have a look at the RMSE:

multi_metric <- metric_set(rmse)
multi_metric(data = test_set1, truth = y_test, estimate = pred_cv_min) %>%
  tibble() %>%
  mutate(.metric = "rmse")

Now we will run the model to predict lnwage based on the test set, using lambda.1se to avoid overfitting:

pred_cv_1se_test <- as.vector(predict(cv_fit, s = "lambda.1se",
                                    newx = test_set_noID))

results <- data.frame(test_set[,1], pred_cv_1se_test) %>%
  rename("lnwage" = pred_cv_1se_test)

Random Forest

The second model we will use will be random forest:

formula_full <- lnwage ~ . -ID
set.seed(1994)
fitControl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv",
                           number = 5,
                           repeats = 3)
rf <- train(formula_full,
            data = train_set1,
            method = "rf",
            trControl = fitControl)

Let’s have a look at the RMSE:

models_pred <- data.frame(rf = predict(rf, newdata = test_set1),
                          truth = test_set1$lnwage)

rmse(models_pred, truth, rf)

Predicting using the Random Forest model:

pred <- predict(rf, newdata = test_set) 
  
results_rf <- data.frame( test_set$ID, pred) %>%
  rename("lnwage" = pred)

Comparing the models

After running the five models, lets compare them based on predictive power:

Creating explainers:

Performance Analysis:

We can see from the model performance analysis that Principle Component (PCR), K-Nearest Neighbor (KNN), Ridge and Boosting models perform very closely where the PCR (principle component) shows the highest RMSE. However, the Random Forest model presents the lowest RMSE by a large difference. Therefore, RF will be our model of choice.

set.seed(167)
mp_glm <- model_performance(ridge_explainer)
mp_pcr <- model_performance(pcr_explainer)
mp_rf <- model_performance(rf_explainer)
mp_knn <- model_performance(knn_explainer)
mp_gbm <- model_performance(gbm_explainer)

plot(mp_rf, mp_pcr, mp_knn, mp_gbm, mp_glm)

plot(mp_rf, mp_pcr, mp_knn, mp_gbm, mp_glm, geom = "boxplot")

Feature importance plot

In this plot we picked the 8 most important features in each model. We can see that except the PCR, all models include the gender (female) feature in the top 5. Moreover, in all models, the most important feature is the edu2 (which is the square value of education years, that is the most correlated feature with the log of wage). However, surprisingly, it is not in the top 8 most important variables in the Boosting model. We also notice that some of the interactions we created were important according to the variable_importance function.

importance_glm <- variable_importance(ridge_explainer)
importance_pcr <- variable_importance(pcr_explainer)
importance_rf <- variable_importance(rf_explainer)
importance_knn <- variable_importance(knn_explainer)
importance_gbm <- variable_importance(gbm_explainer)
plot(importance_glm, importance_pcr, importance_rf, importance_knn, importance_gbm, max_vars = 8)

Conclusion

After looking at the data and adding relevant interactions, we estimated five models: Linear Regression with Ridge Regularization, Principle Component, Random Forest, K Nearest Neighbors and Boosting. We found that the Random Forest and Boosting models have the best predictive power, and therefore we are using those as our final submissions on Kaggle. It is interesting to note, as we would have expected, that the variables with the most predictive power are education, gender, race and geographic location.
